In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle methods**. Create a custom `Window` subclass and return it from `CreateWindow()`:

```csharp
public class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        return new MyWindow(new MainPage());
    }
}

public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* was OnStart  */ }
    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* was OnSleep  */ }
    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* was OnResume */ }
    protected override void OnDestroying() { /* new — app terminating */ }
}
```

**Mapping:**
| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI `Window` |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |
| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` |
| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` |

Alternatively, you can hook platform-specific events in `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents()` for finer-grained control (e.g., Android's `OnPause` vs `OnStop`).
